{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "This volume brings academics together to discuss how this event shaped the role of reason and faith.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Luther's understanding of justification by faith and how this doctrine shaped his understanding of the use and abuse of reason in the academy and in the community.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Luther's vision of the roles of faith and reason reformed the academy's understanding of philosophy, science, and political theory and how this vision might continue to transform contemporary discussions of philosophy, science, ethics, and ecclesiology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "This trust in the reasonableness of God's justice is the foundation of Luther's argument against the sale of indulgences.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "A careful reading of the Ninety-Five Theses reveals that Luther's initial disgust at the sale of indulgences was due to how irrational it would be to one.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Luther's commitment to a reasonable God who demands reasonable things alongside his commitment to a loving God whose mercy defies human reason.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "For Luther, God's justice is reasonable; God's mercy is beyond reason and can only be understood by faith.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Luther's evangelism for faith in the loving promises of the Word of God is the heart of the Reformation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Luther understood this passage contradicted the ethics of Aristotle as taught by the Scholastics.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Faith alone, not reason, can see the value of the righteous person because there is no intrinsic value to the righteous person for reason to see.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Luther's theological-philosophical claims led to phenomenology, existentialism, post-modernism, and contemporary post-ontological structuralism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Luther's philosophical disputations with the Scholastic realists also had implications for the scientists in his time.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Luther's view is that science, when limited in its vocation to the nominalist project, is helpful to society and pleasant for the scientifically minded.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "For Luther, Scripture tells the truth about God's relationship with creation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Luther's view separates Luther's views from that of a humanist like Erasmus who is unsure that theology is anything more than a hypothesis.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Luther's theological claim that justification is by faith alone led to his view of the freedom and equality of the Christian.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Luther's view of justification by faith required Luther to adopt a position of humility towards political theory's ability to create a just city.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Faith tells the believer who she is, and reason helps her decide how to act.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Luther is clear in saying that reason is the greatest attribute which God gave to humans in regard to creating civic laws that best serve one's neighbors.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "No church can be perfected by obedience to the Law: The church is justified by the love of Christ.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The church is holy only by the love of Christ.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
